SIMPLE: enjoin
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enjoin
<hw>En*join"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Enjoined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enjoining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>enjoindre</ets>, L. <ets>injungere</ets> to join into, charge,
enjoin; <ets>in + jungere</ets> to join. See <er>Join</er>, and cf.
<er>Injunction</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay upon, as an order or
command; to give an injunction to; to direct with authority; to order;
to charge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>High matter thou <qex>enjoin'st</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am <qex>enjoined</qex> by oath to observe three things.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To prohibit or restrain by a
judicial order or decree; to put an injunction on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is a suit to <qex>enjoin</qex> the defendants from disturbing
the plaintiffs.</q> <rj><qau>Kent.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Enjoin</xex> has the force of pressing admonition
with authority; as, a parent <xex>enjoins</xex> on his children the duty
of obedience. But it has also the sense of <xex>command</xex>; as, the
duties <xex>enjoined</xex> by God in the moral law. ⟦ldquo⟧This word is
more authoritative than <xex>direct</xex>, and less imperious than
<xex>command</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enjoin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enjoin
<hw>En*join"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To join or unite.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enjoiner</ent>⟦br⟧
